  "prompt": "What was the French New Wave?",
  "response": "The French New Wave (La Nouvelle Vague) was a film movement that emerged in the late 1950s and 1960s in France. It was characterized by its innovative approaches to storytelling and filmmaking, which challenged traditional conventions in cinema. This movement is often seen as a reaction against the established norms of the French film industry at the time, particularly the commercial studio system and the literary adaptations that dominated it. \n\nKey elements of the French New Wave include:\n\n1. **Innovative Narrative Techniques**: Directors of the French New Wave often employed unconventional storytelling methods, including non-linear narratives, improvisation, and ambiguous endings.\n   \n2. **Experimental Editing and Camera Work**: Techniques like jump cuts, long takes, handheld camera work, and rapid changes in tone and style were commonly used.\n\n3. **Realism and On-Location Shooting**: Filmmakers often shot on location rather than using studio sets, capturing a more naturalistic and intimate portrayal of everyday life.\n\n4. **Focus on Youth and Rebellion**: Many films centered around themes of youth, revolt, and the questioning of social norms and traditional values.\n\n5. **Personal Expression**: Directors often imbued their works with a personal touch, making films that reflected their own perspectives and experiences.\n\nProminent figures associated with the French New Wave include directors such as Jean-Luc Godard, Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut, \u00c9ric Rohmer, Jacques Rivette, Claude Chabrol, and Agn\u00e8s Varda. Notable films from this movement include \"Breathless\" (\u00c0 bout de souffle) by Godard, \"The 400 Blows\" (Les Quatre Cents Coups) by Truffaut, and \"Cleo from 5 to 7\" (Cl\u00e9o de 5 \u00e0 7) by Varda.\n\nThe French New Wave had a lasting impact on global cinema, influencing subsequent filmmakers and movements around the world by demonstrating that low-budget, artistically daring films could achieve critical and commercial success.",
